{
  "buggy_files": [
    "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"
  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "azx_resume",
    "azx_runtime_resume"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The HDA Intel driver encounters communication errors during codec probing or operation, which trigger error-handling code that sets chip->single_cmd=1 and/or chip->polling_mode=1. When the device suspends and resumes, azx_resume() and azx_runtime_resume() call azx_init_chip() to re-initialize the hardware. However, they do not reset the error-handling flags (single_cmd, polling_mode, poll_count) before re-initialization. In azx_init_chip(), there is a critical check at line 1222: 'if (!chip->single_cmd)' which only initializes CORB/RIRB if single_cmd=0. Since the error-handling code set single_cmd=1 and this flag is never reset on resume, the CORB/RIRB command interface is not re-initialized after resume. This leaves the device stuck in single_cmd mode, causing codec communication failures that manifest as choppy sound with 2-second silences. The device only recovers after a full reboot (which clears all state). The fix is to reset these flags in azx_resume() and azx_runtime_resume() before calling azx_init_chip()."
}

